[1
Date: October 9, 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: ABCNews [edited
<http://abcnews.go.com/sections/us/DailyNews/WTC_Investigation.html>

FBI Studies Anthrax: Intentional Release Suspected
--------------------------------------------------
Investigators searching for any link between terrorism and 2 cases of
exposures to deadly anthrax in Florida say the incidents were malicious but
not on a scale consistent with a terrorist attack. Federal authorities say
the anthrax spores responsible for the death of a Florida man were not
natural but rather a crude kind made in a laboratory. Identifying the
specific strain of bacteria could provide important leads to the source.
The FBI, now the lead agency in the anthrax probe, has combed through the
headquarters of American Media Inc., where the spores were found. But
traces have been found on only one keyboard, which had been used by a
63-year-old tabloid newspaper editor before he died last week.
The only other place spores have been discovered is in the nasal passages
of a colleague who worked in the building mailroom. That man, 73, is being
treated at a Miami-Dade County hospital. While investigators think a
terrorist attack would more likely have spread anthrax throughout the
entire building, they also say the strain of lab-made bacteria found almost
certainly rules out a lone crackpot. These spores could contain tell-tale
markers that lead investigators to a specific nation or even a laboratory.
U.S. officials - from President Bush on down to Palm Beach County health
officials - say they are taking the anthrax exposure incidents very
seriously. "Thus far it looks like it's a very isolated incident, but any,
any type of incident, any type of information that comes into our
government we take very seriously, because we understand we're dealing with
evil people," the President said today.
Of particular concern is the fact that Mohamed Atta, a suspected ringleader
of the Sept. 11 hijackings, had rented and flown planes out of an airfield
in nearby Lantana, Florida twice during August. Authorities told ABCNEWS
the FBI was running anthrax tests on every one of Atta's possessions they
can find, but preliminary field tests turned up nothing.
Whatever the source of the anthrax spores, the doctors of the deceased
Florida man say he received a huge dose, adding to the belief that he may
have received a package or letter at his desk. "The first look at his
spinal fluid was overwhelming," said Dr. Larry Bush. There was a large
amount of bacteria in the spinal fluid, which is never a good sign. It is a
sign of overwhelming infection."
The coworkers of the deceased Florida man today expressed outrage at what
they said was slow and inadequate federal government response, waiting 4
days to seal off the office building after the anthrax infection was
confirmed.
