[2
Date: 9 Oct 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: CNN [edited
<http://www.cnn.com/2001/HEALTH/10/09/anthrax/index.html>

Link between anthrax, hijackers probed
----------------------------------------------
WEST PALM BEACH, Florida (CNN) -- Federal officials said Tuesday their
investigation into a deadly anthrax infection in Florida included a closer
look at forensic evidence gathered in the weeks since the September 11
terrorist attacks, especially items traced to the suspected hijackers, such
as luggage, documents, and cars.
Employees of American Media in Delray Beach, Florida, worked in temporary
locations Tuesday as law enforcement and health officials scoured their
building for evidence and for further traces of the bacteria. AMI's
building, which also includes offices for the National Enquirer and The
Globe, remained sealed. "The FBI tells us they hope to finish collecting
samples by about mid-day tomorrow," said Lt. Frank Montilli of Boca Raton
Fire-Rescue.
Officials have been working around the clock since Monday. Montilli said
his people have been in charge of decontaminating them as they leave the
building. The procedure includes scrubbing and hosing them down in their
white haz-mat (hazardous material) outfits.
Law enforcement sources said investigators were unable to match The Sun
strain of anthrax with any on record. The closest matches were a strain
from a goat and a strain manufactured in a laboratory. "As we've gathered
more information ... and since no one was sorting wool or tanning hides at
The Sun, it lowers the chance that it was a natural occurrence," said Dr.
Jeffrey Koplan, director of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
in Atlanta. "The evidence is stacking up that indicates it is not
environmental." Both men were affected by the same strain of the bacteria,
which was also the same strain found in trace elements on the computer
keyboard of the deceased man, Agwunobi said.
The FBI was looking into the possibility that anthrax could have gotten
into the building by mail, but sources in Washington said they had no
letter in their possession with traces of anthrax. Sources said
investigators were also checking into former and current employees who may
have had access to the building.
Law enforcement sources in Washington told CNN that investigators were
looking not only at forensic evidence in the AMI building but also at
evidence gathered in the weeks since the deadly September 11 terrorist
attacks in New York, Washington, and Pennsylvania. Investigators were
particularly checking items traced to the suspected hijackers -- luggage,
documents, cars -- for traces of anthrax.
